Exercise: Wrangling date and time data

P4 REEU // Natalie Nelson, PhD

1. Background

In this exercise, you will use lubridate, janitor, and tidyverse functions to organize, summarize, and visualize data on dissolved oxygen concentrations in Lake Mattamuskeet, which is located on the Albemarle-Pamlico Peninsula in Hyde County, eastern North Carolina. Lake Mattamuskeet is part of the Mattamuskeet National Wildlife Refuge managed by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service. Its location along the Atlantic Flyway makes it a pitstop for hundreds of thousands of migratory birds. Ecologically speaking, the lake has had a messy history. From the U.S. Fish and Wildlife webpage: “In the early 20th century, farmers and developers attempted to drain Lake Mattamuskeet, building the world’s largest pumping plant at the time. The lake was drained for certain periods to convert the lake bottom to farmland. Eventually, the effort was abandoned as impractical and too expensive.” Today, the lake is a destination for birders, adventurers, hunters, and fishers. Unfortunately, the lake has experienced severe water quality impairment in recent years, resulting in efforts to restore the lake’s ecosystems.

Figure 1. A satellite image of Lake Mattamuskeet showing the locations of two water quality monitoring stations.

To support continued assessment of the lake’s water quality, there are two water quality monitoring stations installed in the lake: station 0208458893 on the eastern part of the lake and station 0208458892 to the west. At each of these monitoring stations, water temperature, dissolved oxygen, pH, specific conductivity, turbidity, and water depth are measured with field instruments that are programmed to collect data every 15 minutes. These data are made available through the U.S. Geological Survey.

2. Exercise overview

In this exercise, we will analyze dissolved oxygen data collected in the lake from June 01 to December 31, 2017. We will primarily focus on wrangling the data as a function of dates and times in order to address practical challenges that arise when working with datetime data.

Before starting, you should:

  • Open an RStudio Project (.Rproj)

  • Download the script template provided for this exercise on Google Drive, and save it to your project folder

  • Install the dataRetrieval package using the install.packages() function

3. About the data

Measurements of dissolved oxygen are included in the dataset for many time points in 2017. The dissolved oxygen measurements are reported in units of milligrams per liter (mg/L). Dissolved oxygen is often used as a metric for evaluating the health of an aquatic system. When dissolved oxygen dips too low (e.g. below 3 mg/L), aquatic life may die. As a result, drops in dissolved oxygen can lead to “fish kill” events, in which dead fish and other deceased aquatic life die and wash up on shore.

The data can be accessed from the U.S. Geological Survey, station 0208458893. To download the data, we will be using a function in the dataRetrieval package, which was developed by the researchers at the U.S. Geological Survey. Functions in dataRetrieval allow you access a wide range of environmental datasets (e.g., data from USGS monitoring sites, weather data, global climate model outputs for future scenarios, etc.). You are not expected to know how to use dataRetrieval functions - I am just providing this information for reference. All dataRetrieval code needed for the exercise is already provided in the script template.
